.TH CLIPMAN-CLI 1 "July 22, 2026" "Clipman CLI 0.1.0-dev" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
clipman-cli \- access Clipman text history from a terminal
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B clipman-cli
.RI [ global-options ]
.I command
.RI [ command-options ]
.br
.B clipman-cli
.RI [ global-options ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Clipman CLI is an additional command-line client for Clipman text history.
It does not replace the Windows, macOS, Android, or iOS applications.
This development preview is intended for practical testing and feedback;
commands and configuration may change before the first stable CLI release.
It connects to Clipman Server and reads and writes the same encrypted
text-history database as the other clients. Clipman Server requires a
nonblank, preferably unique history password.
.PP
Running without a command opens the accessible line menu when a controlling
terminal is available. Run
.B clipman-cli --help
or
.B clipman-cli COMMAND --help
for the complete current syntax.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B init
Configure and test a server profile. A Clipman Server connection-details file
can supply the server address and token without manually extracting JSON.
.TP
.B status
Check the configured server and selected history. Use
.B --refresh
to download and decrypt the database.
.TP
.B list
List entries, optionally filtered by group, search text, or kind.
.TP
.B get
Write one selected entry to standard output. Template entries resolve unless
.B --raw
is used.
.TP
.B put
Add UTF-8 text from standard input,
.BR --file ,
or
.BR --text .
Standard input is preferred for sensitive text because command arguments can
be visible in the process list.
.TP
.B rm
Delete exactly one entry and add a synchronization tombstone.
.TP
.B pick
Display a numbered list on the controlling terminal and write the selected
entry only to standard output.
.TP
.B menu
Open the line-based history manager. Enter a number to view, "o NUMBER" to
output, "d NUMBER" to delete after confirmation, "r" to refresh, or "q" to
quit.
.TP
.B sync
Download and validate the current server history. This stateless edition has
no offline write queue.
.SH CONFIGURATION
The default configuration is
.I ~/.clipman/config.toml
on Linux and macOS, and
.I %LOCALAPPDATA%\eClipman CLI\econfig.toml
on Windows.
.B CLIPMAN_HOME
changes the data directory.
.B CLIPMAN_CONFIG
or
.B --config
selects another configuration file.
.PP
The history password is resolved from
.BR --password ,
.BR CLIPMAN_PASSWORD ,
saved configuration when explicitly enabled, or a no-echo prompt on the
controlling terminal.
.SH SECURITY
Encrypted CLIPDB2 data is authenticated before decryption or decompression.
The client enforces database, JSON, nesting, entry-count, tombstone-count, and
text-size limits. It does not print server tokens, passwords, full database
identifiers, or clip text in diagnostics.
.PP
On Windows, saved tokens and passwords use DPAPI for the current user. On
Linux and macOS, configuration is restricted to its owner with directory mode
0700 and file mode 0600. An explicitly saved history password on those systems
is stored in that owner-only file.
.PP
The clipman scheme is a convenient name for plain HTTP. Use it only on
loopback, a trusted private network, or a VPN. Use HTTPS across an untrusted
network.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Local input or output failure.
.TP
.B 2
Usage, selection, or confirmation error.
.TP
.B 3
Configuration, permission, or server-authentication error.
.TP
.B 4
Network, server, or synchronization failure.
.TP
.B 5
History password required or incorrect, or database authentication failed.
.TP
.B 6
Requested entry or database not found.
